ntsb3615txt-1-5-5-0-15 The pilot did not possess an instrument rating. 
ntsb3615txt-1-5-5-0-6 The airmet noted occasional ceilings below 1,000 feet and visibility less than 3 miles in fog and precipitation for portions of the en route phase and at the destination. 
ntsb3615txt-1-5-5-0-13 The most conservative weight and balance computation placed the airplane 241.2 pounds over maximum allowable gross weight with a CG location 2.57 inches aft of the rear limit. 
ntsb3615txt-1-5-5-0-7 Mountain obscuration in clouds and precipitation was also forecasted. 
ntsb3615txt-1-5-5-0-2 No record was found that the pilot obtained a preflight weather briefing through an FAA or NWS source. 
ntsb3615txt-1-5-5-0-12 The airplane completed one more turn as it continued to descend to impact about 3 miles west of the airport. 
ntsb3615txt-1-5-5-0-8 The departure airport was surrounded by hilly terrain with tops 1,000 to 3,000 feet above the airport elevation. 
ntsb3615txt-1-5-5-0-3 Surrounding airports were reporting cloud coverage in the area of the accident site between 700 and 1,000 feet above ground level, with visibility's 3 miles or less. 
ntsb3615txt-1-5-5-0-11 The turn continued in a much tighter radius and the airplane lost 500 feet of altitude. 
ntsb3615txt-1-5-5-0-4 A terminal forecast for the area predicted visibility of 3 miles in mist, temporarily 1 mile in mist, between 0400 and 0600. 
ntsb3615txt-1-5-5-0-14 No discrepancies were found with the airplane or engine upon inspection. 
ntsb3615txt-1-5-5-0-9 Recorded radar data tracked the airplane from 500 feet agl to the accident site at 1,112 feet msl (about 600 feet above the airport). 
ntsb3615txt-1-5-5-0-10 The airplane was climbing and completed one 360-degree turn, achieving 2,500 feet msl. 
ntsb3615txt-1-5-5-0-5 An airmet was in effect for ceilings below 1,000 feet and visibility 3 miles in fog and mist for the departure area. 
ntsb3615txt-1-5-5-0-1 The departure was planned for about 0430. 
